{{short description|An oilfield off the coast of South Taranaki, New Zealand}} {{Infobox oil field | name = Maari oilfield | country = [[New Zealand]] | region = | location = [[Taranaki Region|South Taranaki]] | block = | offonshore = offshore | coordinates = | operator = [[OMV]] | operators = | partners = [[OMV]] (69%), Horizon Oil (26%), Cue Taranaki (5%) | image = | caption = | discovery = | start_development = | start_production = 2009 | peak_year = | abandonment = | oil_production_bbl/d = | oil_production_tpy = | production_year_oil = | production_gas_mmcuft/d = | production_gas_mmscm/d = | production_gas_bcm/y = | production_year_gas = | est_oil_bbl = 49 | est_oil_t = | est_gas_bft = | est_gas_bcm = | formations = }}
The '''Maari oilfield''' is an oil reservoir located {{convert|80|km}} off the coast of [[Taranaki Region|South Taranaki]], [[New Zealand]]. Maari is the second largest crude oil field in New Zealand with total reserves of {{convert|49|Moilbbl}}.<ref name="Energy2015">{{cite book|title=Energy in New Zealand 2015| publisher=[[Ministry of Business, Innovation and Employment|MBIE]]| date=August 2015| url=http://www.mbie.govt.nz/info-services/sectors-industries/energy/energy-data-modelling/publications/energy-in-new-zealand| issn=2324-5913}}</ref> Production of oil began in February 2009, and the field is expected to have a productive life of 10 to 15 years. The lead partner for the field is [[OMV|OMV New Zealand]] (69%), with other parties Horizon Oil (26%) and Cue Taranaki (5%).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nbr.co.nz/article/largest-oil-field-goes-full-production-mode-116852| title=Largest oil field goes into full production mode| date=21 December 2009| first=Andrea| last=Deuchrass| newspaper=[[National Business Review]]| accessdate=2010-06-04}}</ref>
